    </div2>
    <div2 id="CONVENTIONS.3">
     <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.HEAD" n="encoding">Encoding</head>
     <p id="CONVENTIONS.100" n="ii.9">&ech; is encoded in &sgml; following the &tei; P4 standard for the encoding of text (&sperbergmcqueenandburnard2001;).<note id="CONVENTIONS.note.0010" n="2"><p>The project was originally encoded according to the P3 standard. It has been corrected and validated against the P4 dtd, however.</p></note> Encoding is for the most part strictly conformant with this standard. The project uses one element not found in the P4 guidelines (&lt;EMEND&gt;), adjusts the content models of three elements (&lt;CELL&gt;, &lt;CORR&gt;, and &lt;W&gt;), and adds attributes to one element (&lt;W&gt;). The edition is noteworthy also for its use of three elements: the &tei; elements &lt;CORR&gt; and &lt;RDGGRP&gt;, and the non-&tei; element &lt;EMEND&gt;. A final subsection discusses the encoding of primary sources in this project.</p>
     <div3 id="CONVENTIONS.3.1">
      <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.1.HEAD">New elements</head>
      <p id="CONVENTIONS.110" n="ii.10">&ech; adds one element to the &tei; standard: &lt;EMEND&gt;. The new element is identical to (a modified form of) the standard &tei; element &lt;CORR&gt; in content, attributes, and syntax. The main difference is conceptual: in this work &lt;CORR&gt; is used to encode physical alterations to the text as it appears in a source document; the &lt;EMEND&gt; element is used to encode alterations and corrections <emph>not</emph> involving the physical adaptation of a source document. An example of a correction is the (scribal) alteration of &ox; <mentioned rend="precorrection">&copyOfo.3a.1;</mentioned> to <mentioned rend="postcorrection">&copyOfo.3a.1;</mentioned>. An example of an emendation is the alteration of the nonsensical reading <mentioned rend="preEmendation">&copyOfyl.8b.2</mentioned> found in all manuscripts of the &ylda; to <mentioned rend="postemendation">&copyOfyl.8b.2;</mentioned> in the critical text.</p>
     </div3>
     <div3 id="CONVENTIONS.3.2">
      <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.HEAD">Changes in content model</head>
      <p id="CONVENTIONS.120" n="ii.11">&ech; alters the content models of three elements: &lt;CELL&gt;, &lt;CORR&gt;, and &lt;W&gt;. In the case of &lt;W&gt;, this change also involves a change in attributes.</p>
      <div4 id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.1">
       <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.1.HEAD">&lt;CELL&gt;</head>
       <p id="CONVENTIONS.130" n="ii.12">The content model of &lt;CELL&gt; has been modified to allow specialPara content (specifically lines and paragraphs).</p>
      </div4>
      <div4 id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.2">
       <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.2.HEAD">&lt;CORR&gt;</head>
       <p id="CONVENTIONS.140" n="ii.13">The content model of &lt;CORR&gt; has been modified to exclude CDATA (the project-specific element &lt;EMEND&gt; shares this model). This change is in keeping with the syntax used in encoding corrections and emendations described below (<ref target="CONVENTIONS.3.4">Syntax</ref>).</p>
      <div4 id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.3">
       <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.2.3.HEAD">&lt;W&gt;</head>
       <p id="CONVENTIONS.150" n="ii.14">The content model of &lt;W&gt; has been modified to allow the inclusion of textual critical elements such as &lt;DAMAGE&gt;, &lt;CORR&gt;, and &lt;UNCLEAR&gt;. This is to allow the encoding of words in diplomatic transcriptions, textual apparatus, and citations from individual manuscripts in the introductory chapters. &lt;W&gt; elements found in the main text of the critical editions are encoded in conformance with the &tei; P4 content model. Two new attributes, <term>basedOn</term> and <term>copiedFrom</term>, have also been added to the element. These are discussed below.</p>
      </div4>
     </div3>
     <div3 id="CONVENTIONS.3.3">
      <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.3.HEAD">Attributes</head>
      <p id="CONVENTIONS.160" n="ii.15">The attributes <term>basedOn</term> and <term>copiedFrom</term> have been added to &lt;W&gt;. These elements take IDREF datatypes. <term>basedOn</term> is used to refer to the source of an editorially modified form. Modification may involve the removal of diplomatic information, alterations in the use of capital letters, or similar minor modifications. Most readings of the &aelda;, for example, are derived from &mx;; the association between the editorial and witness readings is indicated by the use of the specific IDREF for the relevant manuscript form on the <term>basedOn</term> attribute of the editorial reading. <term>copiedFrom</term> is used to indicate identity with a form used elsewhere in the project. Citations in the introductory chapters from individual witnesses, readings, or apparatus entries, for example, always have the IDREF of the source reading on the <term>copiedFrom</term> attribute.</p>
     </div3>
     <div3 id="CONVENTIONS.3.4">
      <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.HEAD" n="syntax">Syntax</head>
      <div4 id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1">
       <head id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1.HEAD">Element Nesting</head>
       <p id="CONVENTIONS.170" n="ii.16">Three elements in &ech; are always used with nested data: &lt;CORR&gt;, &lt;EMEND&gt;, and &lt;RDGGRP&gt;. In the case of the first two elements, this nesting involves a change in content model; in the case of the third, the nesting canonises a possible syntax.</p>
       <div5 id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1.1">
	<head id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1.1.HEAD">&lt;CORR&gt;, &lt;EMEND&gt;</head>
	<p id="CONVENTIONS.180" n="ii.17">The &tei; element &lt;CORR&gt; and its project-specific cousin &lt;EMEND&gt; are used in a fashion at variance with that suggested by the &tei; guidelines. In &ech;, corrections and emendations are understood as processes by which an original form is altered by deletion and/or addition. For this reason, &lt;CORR&gt; and &lt;EMEND&gt; tags always contain at least one &lt;ADD&gt; or &lt;DEL&gt; element. Thus, for example, the &ox; reading <mentioned rend="diplomatic">&copyOfo.3a.1;</mentioned> is encoded as follows (attributes have been simplified for demonstration purposes):</p>
	<quote>
	 <p><c>&amp;#x01BF;</c>er&lt;corr&gt; &lt;del rend="overwriting"&gt;o&lt;/del&gt;&lt;add place="overwriting"&gt;a&lt;/add&gt;&lt;/corr&gt;</p>
	</quote>
	<p rend="noindent">The emended &ylda; reading <mentioned lang="ANG">&copyOfyl.8b.2;</mentioned>, similarly, is encoded as follows (attributes have been simplified for demonstration purposes):</p>
	<quote>
	 <p>t&lt;emend&gt;&lt;del&gt;i&lt;/del&gt; &lt;add&gt;eo&lt;/add&gt;&lt;/emend&gt;d&lt;emend&gt; &lt;del&gt;a&lt;/del&gt;&lt;add&gt;e&lt;/add&gt; &lt;/emend&gt;</p>
	</quote>
	<p id="CONVENTIONS.190" n="ii.18">This usage is an adaptation of the recommendations for the encoding of substitution given in &sperbergmcqueenandburnard2001; &sect; 18.1.5; it may indeed represent an improvement, since the nesting of &lt;DEL&gt; and &lt;ADD&gt; elements within &lt;CORR&gt; or &lt;EMEND&gt; makes their relationship explicit (cf. &sect; 18.1.5) and anticipates some aspects of the proposed (P5) &lt;CHOICE&gt; element. A potential problem with this usage, however, involves the change in scope. In the &tei; guidelines, &lt;CORR&gt; is understood as a <socalled>mirror image</socalled> of &lt;SIC&gt; and as sharing approximately the same scope as &lt;ADD&gt; and &lt;DEL&gt;. By seeing &lt;CORR&gt; as a process of addition and deletion rather than a state of correction, the modified syntax in this edition removes the equivalency with &lt;SIC&gt;; by nesting &lt;ADD&gt; and &lt;DEL&gt;, the project also requires the elements to have a difference in scope: &lt;CORR&gt; (and &lt;EMEND&gt;) are used to describe a process of correction or emendation; &lt;ADD&gt; and &lt;DEL&gt; are used to describe an actual state of deletion or addition.</p>
       </div5>
       <div5 id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1.2">
	<head id="CONVENTIONS.3.4.1.2.HEAD">Readings and reading groups</head>
	<p id="CONVENTIONS.210" n="ii.19">With one exception, &lt;RDG&gt;s are always nested in three &lt;RDGGRP&gt; elements. The exception is the parallel witness apparatus (where &lt;RDG&gt; elements are collected in a single &lt;RDGGRP&gt;). Each reading group corresponds to a bracket in the analytic all witness view discussed above. The apparatus for <mentioned lang="ang">&copyOfex.4b.1;</mentioned> discussed above is thus encoded as in the following example ([&lt;<xref doc="ex4b1.htm">ex4b1.htm</xref>&gt;])</p>
